147","1267":"1267","1245":"1245","1222":"1222","Abt 4 January 1222":"circa 4 januari 1222","1185":"1185","1140":"1140","Abt 1190":"circa 1190","Abt 1228":"circa 1228","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Rotherfield, Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, England","Rotherfield Greys, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Rotherfield Greys, Oxfordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1190–Abt 1228":"about 1190–about 1228","1190–1228":"1190–1228","1185–1245":"1185–1245","1205–1245":"1205–1245","1222–1267":"1222–1267","1147–1185":"1147–1185","1140–Female":"1140–Deceased","1228":"1228","1190":"1190","1205":"1205","1147":"1147","1267":"1267","1245":"1245","1222":"1222","Abt 4 January 1222":"about 4 January 1222","1185":"1185","1140":"1140","Abt 1190":"about 1190","Abt 1228":"about 1228","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Rotherfield, Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, England","Rotherfield Greys, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Rotherfield Greys, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"St","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["1  French: habitational name from any of the places so called, for example in Normandy, named from a religious dedication to a (male) St. Clair.","2  North American variant spelling of   St  .   Claire  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Claire","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Clare  .","Variant of   Clair  , an altered form of German   Klare  .","French: variant of   Clair  ."]}]},{"name":"Luce","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","from the Old French and Middle English female personal name <i>Luce</i>, <i>Lucy</i>, from Latin   Lucia  .","habitational name from Lucé (Orne), transported to England by the Normans."],"variants":[{"name":"Lucia","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Rocco, Domenic, Francesco, Marcello, Pietro, Sal, Agostino, Biagio, Carmine, Cesare, Ferdinando.","Italian (southern); Spanish (<b>Lucía</b>): from the female personal name <i>Lucia</i>, <i>Lucía</i>, feminine variant of Latin   Lucius  . It was borne by a young Sicilian maiden and an aged Roman widow, both of whom were martyred under Diocletian and are venerated as saints.","English: from a Latinized form of   Luce  , or occasionally from   Loose  ."]},{"name":"Lucey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Maeve, Niall.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Luasaigh</b>, an altered form of <b>Mac Cluasaigh</b>, a Cork name meaning ‘son of <i>Cluasach</i>’, a byname originally denoting someone with large or otherwise noticeable ears (from <i>cluas</i> ‘ear’).","English: variant of   Luce   1."]},{"name":"Luse","meanings":["Probably an altered form or a variant of English   Luce  ."]}]},{"name":"Beatrix","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Late Latin personal name, which was borne by a saint martyred in Rome, together with Saints Faustinus and Simplicius, in the early 4th century. The original form of the name was probably <i>Viatrix</i>, a feminine version of <i>Viator</i> ‘voyager (through life)’, which was a favourite name among early Christians. This was then altered by association with Latin <i>Beatus</i> ‘blessed’ (<i>Via-</i> and <i>Bea-</i> sometimes being pronounced the same in Late Latin).  See also  Beatrice ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Beatrix St Luce was born about 1190, in Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, William de Seynthice de Saint Luce, was 44 and her mother, Avicia de Sculcotes, was 52. She had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Sir Robert de Grey of Rotherfield. She died about 1228, in Rotherfield Greys, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 40."},"et":{"Abt 1190–Abt 1228":"umbes 1190–umbes 1228","1190–1228"